IRAQI CONTROL: Iraqi policemen paraded Wednesday during a ceremonial transfer of security duties to Iraqi forces in Diwaniya, a city south of Baghdad.

American-led forces handed over control of the Qadisiyah province to the Iraqi government, reflecting the improvement in security across the country. Iraqi leaders are now seeking a timeline from the U.S. for the withdrawal of American forces.

MORE BLASTS: Pakistani policemen helped injured colleagues after a suicide attack in Islamabad Sunday.

One day after the deadly suicide bombing in Islamabad that killed 18 people, most of them police officers, a string of five explosions within an hour on Monday wounded at least 25 people in the southern Pakistani city of Karachi.

• Explosions Wound 25 in Pakistan a Day After Bomber Killed 18

THAT'S A MOUTHFUL: Joey Chestnut, right, celebrated Friday after winning the annual Nathan's hot-dog-eating contest in Coney Island, Brooklyn.

Joey Chestnut reclaimed the top spot at the annual hot dog eating contest in Coney Island Friday after first tying with archrival Takeru Kobayashi in a 10-minute chow-down and then beating him in a five-dog eat-off.
link_name: WSJ Photography

status_message:
CALIFORNIA BURNING: The Piute fire burned out of control as more than 1,400 wildfires continued to scorch more than 660 square miles in California Tuesday.

California Gov. Arnold Schwarzenegger ordered 200 National Guard troops to report for fire training to relieve weary firefighters battling statewide blazes, marking the first time the guard has been asked to send soldiers to join ground-based firefights since 1977.

• National Guard to Join Battle Against California Wildfires

status_message:
GREEN OLYMPICS: Chinese fishermen pitched in to help clean up the east coast of Qingdao Monday.

China's pledge to stage a "Green Olympics" has taken on a worrying meaning at the sailing-venue city of Qingdao, about 340 miles southeast of Beijing, where an algae bloom has spread along the coastline.
